“The fool worries as if he were his own protector. Yet he owns nothing—not even himself.”— Dhammapada, Verse 62
“…might look about, thinking, ‘Is there anyone who can save me?’—so too should you train yourself.” — Anguttara Nikāya, 5:57
“…long is the cycle of births and deaths to the foolish who do not know the true path.” — Dhammapada, Verse 60
“All conditioned things are impermanent. When one sees this with wisdom, one turns away from suffering.” (Dhammapada, Verse 277)
“The world is afflicted by death and decay. But the wise do not grieve, having realized the nature of the world.” (Sutta Nipata)
“All life is bound up with suffering.”
“Life is swept along, short is the life span; no shelters exist for one who has reached old age.” (Dhammapada, Verse 147)
“This world is blind! Here there are few who clearly see.”(Dhammapada, Verse 174)
“All is burning. The eye is burning, forms are burning, eye-consciousness is burning… burning with the fire of lust, hatred, and delusion.” (Samyutta Nikaya 35.28, Fire Sermon)
“Like a fish pulled from its watery home and thrown on dry ground, our mind trembles all over, struggling to escape the dominion of Mara.”(Dhammapada, Verse 34)


